      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Kitchen Renovations Before Selling in Brisbane: Which Upgrades Pay Off and Which Are Wasted Spend
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The kitchen is the single most influential room in most buyers' purchase decision. Here is what to spend, what to leave alone, and what consistently returns multiples at sale.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Almost every seller asks the same question: should we renovate the kitchen before selling, and if so, how far should we go? The answer depends on the starting condition, the price bracket, and the likely buyer profile, and the difference between a smart kitchen investment and a wasteful one is often tens of thousands of dollars in net result. The kitchen is the single most influential room in most buyers' purchase decisions, which is exactly why it deserves careful thought rather than the default reflex of either doing nothing or going all in on a full renovation.</p>

      <p>Buyers spend more time in the kitchen during inspections than any other room. They open cupboards, run their hands along the benchtop, look inside the oven, check the dishwasher, and stand at the bench imagining their own life happening there. An outdated kitchen creates a strong negative first impression that can cap the property's appeal regardless of how good the bathrooms, bedrooms, and outdoor areas are. Conversely, a well-presented kitchen often raises the buyer's view of the entire property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'outdated' actually means to buyers</h2>

      <p>It is helpful to be specific about what makes a kitchen feel old. Buyers do not articulate it this way, but their reactions cluster around a recognisable set of features.</p>

      <p>Laminate benchtops in colours that signal pre-2010 are the single biggest visual cue. Yellow and beige tones, dark wood patterns, marbled cream finishes, and high-gloss coloured laminates all read as dated even if the laminate itself is in good condition. Stone benchtops, even modest engineered stone, read as current.</p>

      <p>Older appliances are the second cue. A gas cooktop that is more than 15 years old, a wall oven with analogue dials, or a freestanding oven with visible scorching all signal that the kitchen has not been touched in a long time. Buyers do not always know exactly how old the appliances are, but they recognise the signs.</p>

      <p>Small dated cabinetry without soft-close hinges is a quieter signal but a real one. Slamming cupboard doors are something every buyer notices at the inspection without consciously registering it.</p>

      <p>Fluorescent overhead lighting and yellow-tinted downlights make the kitchen look tired even when everything else is reasonable. Lighting is one of the most overlooked but high-impact features.</p>

      <p>Tiled splashbacks with patterned tiles or visible grout discolouration date a kitchen quickly. Plain white subway tiles, glass panels, or stone slab splashbacks all read as current.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cosmetic-only refresh: best ROI</h2>

      <p>For a kitchen that is structurally sound but visually dated, a cosmetic refresh consistently produces the best return on investment of any kitchen work.</p>

      <p>Painting cabinetry doors and bench frames in a neutral colour is the highest-impact single move. A professional spray finish on existing cabinets typically costs $600 to $1,500 depending on the kitchen size and number of doors. Done well, it can transform the appearance of a kitchen entirely.</p>

      <p>Replacing cabinet handles is a small spend with a disproportionate effect. New handles in a current style cost $200 to $500 for a typical kitchen and immediately update the look.</p>

      <p>Replacing the splashback with simple white or grey tiles or a glass panel costs $800 to $2,500 and removes one of the most ageing features of older kitchens. The effort is real, and you should expect some kitchen downtime, but the visual change is significant.</p>

      <p>Replacing dated tap fittings with a modern pull-out mixer costs $300 to $600 and is a quick weekend job for a plumber. Buyers notice taps more than sellers expect.</p>

      <p>Adding new pendant lighting over an island bench costs $300 to $700 and creates a focal point in photographs. The visual impact in marketing photography is often larger than the in-person impact.</p>

      <p>A full cosmetic refresh in this format typically costs $2,200 to $5,800 and consistently returns 3 to 5 times the investment in sale price for inner Brisbane homes. There are very few interior investments with that kind of consistent payoff.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The partial renovation: strong ROI in older homes</h2>

      <p>For an older Queenslander or post-war home where the cosmetic refresh would not be enough to lift the kitchen to a comparable standard, a partial renovation is often the right answer.</p>

      <p>New benchtops in stone, either engineered or natural, cost $3,000 to $6,500 for a typical kitchen. Stone benchtops are the single most reliable visual signal of a current kitchen, and replacing tired laminate with stone produces a dramatic improvement.</p>

      <p>Replacing the oven and cooktop with modern integrated appliances costs $2,500 to $5,000 depending on brand and specification. Mid-tier appliances from Bosch, Miele entry, or Westinghouse are the right level for inner Brisbane sales. Going further upmarket rarely pays back.</p>

      <p>A new sink and tapware costs $500 to $1,200. Undermount sinks in stone benchtops feel current; drop-in sinks read as older.</p>

      <p>Lighting and minor electrical updates cost $500 to $1,500. Replacing fluorescents with LED downlights, adding pendant lighting, and ensuring the light colour temperature is consistent throughout makes a meaningful difference.</p>

      <p>A partial renovation in this format typically costs $6,500 to $14,200 and returns 1.5 to 2.5 times the investment in older homes where the starting condition was genuinely dated. The return is lower than a cosmetic refresh because the spend is higher, but the absolute dollar gain is often larger.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The full kitchen renovation: variable ROI</h2>

      <p>A complete demolition and rebuild of the kitchen is a very different proposition. Costs in inner Brisbane typically run $25,000 to $60,000 or more, depending on the kitchen size, the cabinetry specification, the layout changes, and the appliance choices.</p>

      <p>The return on a full renovation depends entirely on the starting point and the buyer profile. If the existing kitchen is genuinely awful, with structural problems, water damage, mould, or layout issues that materially affect daily use, a full renovation can be highly worthwhile. The buyer pool widens significantly when the kitchen issue is removed, and the achieved price often justifies the spend.</p>

      <p>If the existing kitchen is functional but dated, a full renovation usually does not pay back. The cosmetic or partial route delivers most of the buyer perception benefit at a fraction of the cost. The marginal gain from going further rarely returns its investment.</p>

      <p>If the property is on land likely to be redeveloped, a full renovation is almost always wasted money. A buyer who is going to demolish the home will not pay for a new kitchen they intend to remove.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NOT to do before selling</h2>

      <p>Some kitchen choices that look like upgrades actually narrow the buyer pool or fail to return their cost.</p>

      <p>Luxury appliances such as Sub-Zero refrigerators, La Cornue ranges, or Wolf cooktops are personal indulgences. Buyers do not pay for them at resale. If you have an existing luxury appliance, take it with you and replace it with a mid-tier equivalent before listing.</p>

      <p>Highly customised storage solutions narrow the buyer pool. A kitchen designed around a specific person's cooking habits feels like someone else's kitchen to the buyer. Generic storage configurations sell better than bespoke ones.</p>

      <p>Trendy colour cabinetry such as sage green, navy, or terracotta dates quickly. What feels fresh in 2024 reads as dated in 2027. White, off-white, light grey, and natural timber finishes have the longest shelf life.</p>

      <p>Renovating just one section of the kitchen while the rest remains dated produces a worse outcome than doing nothing. A new stone benchtop next to old yellow laminate looks worse than an honest dated kitchen.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The inspection-day signal</h2>

      <p>A fresh, clean, neutral kitchen signals 'move-in ready' to buyers. The opposite signal, of clutter, mess, and visible wear, is harder to overcome than sellers expect. Several practical points matter at the inspection itself.</p>

      <p>Clear the benches. The visual impact of empty bench surfaces is enormous. Even a cosmetically dated kitchen looks substantially better when the benches are clear of toasters, kettles, knife blocks, dish racks, and miscellaneous bottles.</p>

      <p>Ensure the oven, cooktop, dishwasher, and rangehood are clean and functional. Buyers do open the oven. They do check the dishwasher. A grimy oven sets a strong negative tone for the rest of the inspection.</p>

      <p>Replace any obviously broken or worn items. A cracked benchtop edge, a missing cupboard handle, a leaking tap: these are read as deferred maintenance and projected onto the rest of the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The value calculation</h2>

      <p>For a property in the $1 million plus range in inner Brisbane, $5,000 to $10,000 of well-targeted cosmetic kitchen work routinely adds $20,000 to $40,000 to the sale price. This is the most reliable interior return available short of structural work.</p>

      <p>Diminishing returns kick in past about $20,000 of kitchen spend. Each additional dollar tends to return progressively less. The exception is when the starting condition is so poor that a partial or full renovation is genuinely required to widen the buyer pool, but those situations should be assessed honestly rather than assumed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Run the assessment in this order. If the kitchen is functional but visually dated, invest in a cosmetic refresh: paint, handles, splashback, taps, lighting. The ROI is reliably strong and the disruption is minimal.</p>

      <p>If the kitchen has structural problems, water issues, or layout flaws that materially limit daily use, consider a partial renovation focused on the worst issues. Do not extend the project beyond what is genuinely needed.</p>

      <p>If the property is on land likely to be redeveloped, do minimal kitchen work. Clean, declutter, and replace any obviously failed items, but do not invest in finishes that will be demolished.</p>

      <p>Always finish whatever work you start. A half-done renovation looks worse than a dated original. A clear timeline, a competent tradesperson, and a finishing date well before the listing date are the practical conditions for any pre-sale kitchen investment.</p>

      <p>The kitchen is the most influential room in the inspection, and that is exactly why it rewards thoughtful, targeted spending rather than reflexive renovation.</p>

